    impact:
        '''Kemenangan Theseus membebaskan Athena dari upeti darah kepada Kreta dan menandai peralihan kekuasaan dari Kreta ke daratan Yunani. Kepulangannya membawanya naik takhta, dan tradisi menganggapnya sebagai pahlawan pendiri yang menyatukan wilayah Attika menjadi satu negara-kota. Kematian Aigeus memberi nama abadi bagi Laut Aigea. Kisah ini juga memicu babak Daedalus dan Icarus, karena kemarahan Minos atas pengkhianatan Ariadne.''',
    impactEn:
        '''Theseus\'s victory freed Athens from its blood tribute to Crete and marked the shift of power from Crete to the Greek mainland. His return raised him to the throne, and tradition regards him as the founder-hero who unified the region of Attica into a single city-state. Aegeus\'s death gave the Aegean Sea its enduring name. This tale also set in motion the episode of Daedalus and Icarus, born of Minos\'s fury at Ariadne\'s betrayal.''',
    meaning:
        '''Benang Ariadne menjadi lambang abadi akal yang menuntun manusia keluar dari kebingungan; frasa "benang Ariadne" hingga kini berarti petunjuk yang membebaskan dari kerumitan. Labirin melambangkan perjalanan batin menghadapi ketakutan tersembunyi, sedangkan Minotaur mewakili sisi kebinatangan yang harus ditaklukkan. Tragedi layar hitam mengajarkan betapa kelalaian kecil dapat berbuah bencana besar dan tak terbalikkan.''',
    meaningEn:
        '''Ariadne\'s thread became an enduring symbol of reason guiding a person out of confusion; the phrase "Ariadne\'s thread" still means a clue that leads one out of complexity. The Labyrinth represents the inner journey to confront a hidden fear, while the Minotaur embodies the bestial nature that must be conquered. The tragedy of the black sail teaches how a small negligence can bear great and irreversible catastrophe.''',
  ),
  MythStory(
    id: 'greek-icarus',
    mythology: 'Greek',
    icon: '🪶',
    title: 'Icarus dan Daedalus',
    titleEn: 'Icarus and Daedalus',
    summary:
        'Terkurung di Kreta, sang penemu Daedalus membuat sayap dari bulu dan lilin; putranya Icarus terbang terlalu dekat matahari, lilinnya meleleh, dan ia jatuh ke laut.',
    summaryEn:
        'Trapped in Crete, the inventor Daedalus fashions wings of feathers and wax; his son Icarus flies too near the sun, the wax melts, and he plunges into the sea.',
    timeline: 'Zaman Pahlawan · Kisah Kreta',
    timelineEn: 'Age of Heroes · The Cretan Tales',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Latar Belakang',
        headingEn: 'Background',
        body:
            '''Daedalus adalah perajin dan penemu terbesar zamannya, keturunan raja-raja Athena, yang termasyhur karena patung, mesin, dan bangunannya yang menakjubkan. Karena kecemburuan, ia pernah membunuh keponakannya yang berbakat, lalu melarikan diri ke Kreta dan mengabdi kepada Raja Minos. Di sanalah ia membangun Labirin yang termasyhur untuk mengurung Minotaur. Namun ketika putri Minos, Ariadne, membantu Theseus meloloskan diri dengan benang yang Daedalus sendiri sarankan, Raja Minos murka besar. Sebagai hukuman atas pengkhianatan itu, Minos mengurung Daedalus bersama putranya, Icarus, di dalam menara — sebagian versi menyebut di dalam Labirin ciptaannya sendiri. Minos menguasai seluruh laut dengan armadanya, sehingga pelarian lewat kapal mustahil. Daedalus pun mencari jalan lain untuk kabur.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''Daedalus was the greatest craftsman and inventor of his age, descended from the kings of Athens, renowned for his marvellous statues, machines, and buildings. Out of jealousy, he had once killed his gifted nephew, then fled to Crete and served King Minos. There he built the famous Labyrinth to imprison the Minotaur. But when Minos\'s daughter, Ariadne, helped Theseus escape with the thread that Daedalus himself had suggested, King Minos flew into a great rage. As punishment for that betrayal, Minos imprisoned Daedalus together with his son, Icarus, in a tower — some versions say within the very Labyrinth of his own making. Minos controlled all the seas with his fleet, so escape by ship was impossible. And so Daedalus sought another way to flee.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Sayap dari Bulu dan Lilin',
        headingEn: 'Wings of Feather and Wax',
        body:
            '''Karena Minos menutup jalur darat dan laut, Daedalus menyimpulkan bahwa satu-satunya jalan yang tak dikuasai raja adalah udara. Ia pun mulai mengumpulkan bulu-bulu burung, dari yang terbesar hingga yang terkecil, lalu menyusunnya berderet menyerupai sayap sungguhan. Bulu-bulu itu ia ikat dengan benang di bagian tengah dan direkatkan dengan lilin lebah di bagian bawah, kemudian ia lengkungkan sedikit agar menyerupai sayap burung asli. Icarus muda ikut membantu ayahnya, bermain-main dengan bulu yang beterbangan dan meremas lilin yang lunak, tanpa menyadari bahwa ia sedang mengutak-atik alat yang menentukan nasibnya. Setelah dua pasang sayap selesai, Daedalus mengenakannya, mengepakkannya sejenak, dan tubuhnya benar-benar terangkat ke udara — penemuan yang belum pernah dicapai manusia mana pun sebelumnya.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''Since Minos had sealed the routes by land and sea, Daedalus concluded that the one path the king did not control was the air. He began to gather the feathers of birds, from the largest to the smallest, and arranged them in rows to resemble true wings. He bound the feathers with thread at the middle and fastened them with beeswax at the base, then curved them slightly to imitate a real bird\'s wing. Young Icarus helped his father, playing with the drifting feathers and kneading the soft wax, unaware that he was tampering with the very device that would decide his fate. When two pairs of wings were finished, Daedalus put them on, beat them for a moment, and his body truly rose into the air — an invention no human had ever achieved before.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Peringatan Sang Ayah',
        headingEn: 'The Father\'s Warning',
        body:
            '''Sebelum lepas landas, Daedalus memasangkan sayap pada bahu putranya dan memberinya nasihat sungguh-sungguh. Ia memperingatkan Icarus agar terbang di jalur tengah: jangan terlalu rendah, sebab uap air laut akan membasahi dan memberati sayapnya; jangan pula terlalu tinggi, sebab panas matahari akan melelehkan lilin yang merekatkan bulu-bulu itu. "Ikuti aku, terbanglah di ketinggian sedang," pesannya. Dengan tangan gemetar dan pipi basah oleh air mata, sang ayah mencium putranya untuk terakhir kali — tanpa ia tahu bahwa itu benar-benar yang terakhir. Keduanya lalu mengepakkan sayap dan melayang meninggalkan menara. Para gembala dan nelayan yang menengadah dari bawah tercengang menyaksikan dua sosok manusia melayang di langit bagai dewa, dan mengira mereka makhluk ilahi yang mampu menaklukkan angkasa.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''Before taking off, Daedalus fitted the wings to his son\'s shoulders and gave him earnest counsel. He warned Icarus to fly a middle course: not too low, lest the sea\'s moisture soak and weigh down his wings; and not too high, lest the heat of the sun melt the wax that held the feathers together. "Follow me, fly at a moderate height," he urged. With trembling hands and cheeks wet with tears, the father kissed his son for the last time — not knowing it truly would be the last. The two then beat their wings and soared away from the tower. Shepherds and fishermen who looked up from below were astonished to see two human figures gliding across the sky like gods, and took them for divine beings who had conquered the heavens.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Terbang Terlalu Tinggi',
        headingEn: 'Flying Too High',
        body:
            '''Untuk beberapa saat keduanya terbang selamat, melintasi pulau-pulau di Laut Aigea. Namun keajaiban terbang membuat Icarus muda mabuk gembira. Melupakan peringatan ayahnya, ia terbang semakin tinggi, terpesona oleh langit luas, seolah hendak menggapai surga sendiri. Semakin dekat ia ke matahari, semakin panas udara di sekelilingnya, hingga lilin yang merekatkan bulu-bulunya mulai melunak lalu meleleh. Satu per satu bulu terlepas dari sayapnya dan berhamburan tertiup angin. Icarus mengepakkan lengannya yang telah gundul dengan panik, tetapi tak ada lagi yang menahannya di udara. Ia jatuh menjerit memanggil ayahnya, meluncur turun menembus udara, hingga tubuhnya terhempas ke laut biru dan tenggelam. Air yang menelannya sejak itu dikenang dengan nama Laut Ikaria, mengabadikan tragedi sang pemuda.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''For a while the two flew safely, crossing the islands of the Aegean Sea. But the wonder of flight intoxicated young Icarus with joy. Forgetting his father\'s warning, he flew higher and higher, enchanted by the boundless sky, as if to reach heaven itself. The nearer he drew to the sun, the hotter the air around him became, until the wax that bound his feathers began to soften and then melt. One by one the feathers loosened from his wings and scattered on the wind. Icarus beat his now-bare arms in panic, but nothing held him in the air any longer. He fell crying out for his father, plunging down through the air, until his body struck the blue sea and sank. The waters that swallowed him have since been remembered as the Icarian Sea, immortalizing the young man\'s tragedy.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Duka Daedalus',
        headingEn: 'The Grief of Daedalus',
        body:
            '''Daedalus, yang terbang di depan, menoleh memanggil nama putranya, "Icarus! Icarus!" tetapi tak ada jawaban. Ia hanya melihat bulu-bulu mengambang di permukaan laut, menyadari dengan hancur bahwa putranya telah tenggelam. Dengan hati remuk, sang penemu menemukan jenazah Icarus yang terdampar dan menguburkannya di sebuah pulau yang kemudian dinamai Ikaria untuk mengenangnya. Daedalus melanjutkan pelariannya hingga tiba di Sisilia, tempat ia berlindung pada Raja Kokalos. Minos yang keras kepala mengejar sang perajin ke seluruh penjuru, tetapi akhirnya sang raja Kreta sendiri tewas di Sisilia karena tipu daya. Dalam dukanya yang mendalam, Daedalus menggantungkan sayapnya sebagai persembahan di kuil Apollo, bersumpah tak akan pernah terbang lagi, sebab penemuan terbesarnya telah merenggut nyawa yang paling ia kasihi.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''Daedalus, flying ahead, turned to call his son\'s name, "Icarus! Icarus!" but there was no answer. He saw only feathers floating on the surface of the sea, and realized with heartbreak that his son had drowned. With a shattered heart, the inventor found Icarus\'s washed-up body and buried it on an island afterward named Icaria in his memory. Daedalus continued his flight until he reached Sicily, where he took refuge with King Cocalus. The stubborn Minos pursued the craftsman everywhere, but in the end the Cretan king himself died in Sicily through a stratagem. In his deep grief, Daedalus hung up his wings as an offering in the temple of Apollo, vowing never to fly again, for his greatest invention had claimed the life he loved most.''',
      ),
    ],
