    chronologyEn: [
      'Eris throws a golden apple inscribed "For the fairest" at the wedding of Peleus and Thetis.',
      'Hera, Athena, and Aphrodite quarrel over the apple.',
      'Zeus commands Hermes to bring them to Paris on Mount Ida.',
      'The three goddesses bribe Paris with power, glory, and love.',
      'Paris chooses Aphrodite for the promise of Helen\'s love.',
      'Paris sails to Sparta and carries Helen to Troy.',
      'Menelaus and Agamemnon gather the kings of Greece, invoking the suitors\' oath.',
      'A fleet of a thousand ships assembles at Aulis to attack Troy.',
      'The Trojan War breaks out, with the gods divided in support of both sides.',
    ],
    impact:
        '''Penghakiman Paris adalah percikan yang menyulut Perang Troya, konflik sentral dalam mitologi Yunani yang menewaskan generasi pahlawan di kedua pihak. Keputusan itu menentukan keberpihakan para dewa: Hera dan Athena membela Yunani, Aphrodite membela Troya. Dari akar peristiwa ini mengalir seluruh kisah Iliad, kejatuhan Troya, serta pengembaraan para pahlawan yang pulang, membentuk fondasi bagi sastra epik Barat.''',
    impactEn:
        '''The Judgment of Paris was the spark that ignited the Trojan War, the central conflict of Greek mythology that destroyed a generation of heroes on both sides. The decision determined the gods\' allegiances: Hera and Athena backing the Greeks, Aphrodite backing Troy. From the root of this event flowed the entire tale of the Iliad, the fall of Troy, and the wanderings of the returning heroes, forming the foundation of Western epic literature.''',
    meaning:
        '''Penghakiman Paris melambangkan pilihan manusia di antara nilai-nilai yang bersaing: kekuasaan, kebijaksanaan, atau cinta. Paris memilih hasrat di atas kearifan dan kekuasaan, dan kegegabahan itu berbuah kehancuran, mencerminkan peringatan Yunani tentang bahaya menyerah pada nafsu. Kisah ini juga menegaskan gagasan bahwa peristiwa sepele — sebuah apel dan sengketa kesombongan — dapat menggerakkan takdir bangsa-bangsa dan menggenapi kehendak para dewa yang tak terhindarkan.''',
    meaningEn:
        '''The Judgment of Paris symbolizes the human choice among competing values: power, wisdom, or love. Paris chose desire over wisdom and power, and that rashness bore ruin, reflecting the Greek warning about the dangers of surrendering to passion. The tale also affirms the idea that a trivial event — an apple and a dispute of vanity — can set in motion the fate of nations and fulfill the inescapable will of the gods.''',
  ),
  MythStory(
    id: 'greek-trojan-horse',
    mythology: 'Greek',
    icon: '🐴',
    title: 'Kuda Troya',
    titleEn: 'The Trojan Horse',
    summary:
        'Setelah sepuluh tahun pengepungan, bangsa Yunani menyembunyikan prajurit terbaik di dalam kuda kayu raksasa, tipu daya yang akhirnya meruntuhkan Troya dari dalam.',
    summaryEn:
        'After ten years of siege, the Greeks hide their best warriors inside a giant wooden horse, a ruse that finally topples Troy from within.',
    timeline: 'Zaman Pahlawan · Kejatuhan Troya',
    timelineEn: 'Age of Heroes · The Fall of Troy',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Latar Belakang',
        headingEn: 'Background',
        body:
            '''Selama sepuluh tahun bangsa Yunani mengepung Troya tanpa mampu menembus tembok kotanya yang kokoh, yang menurut kisah dibangun oleh dewa Poseidon dan Apollo. Perang telah merenggut nyawa para pahlawan besar: Hektor sang pembela Troya gugur di tangan Akhilleus, dan Akhilleus sendiri kemudian tewas oleh panah Paris yang menembus tumitnya. Pasukan Yunani lelah dan putus asa, sementara Troya tetap berdiri tegak di balik tembok abadinya. Serangan langsung terbukti sia-sia. Maka Odysseus, raja Ithaka yang termasyhur karena kecerdikannya, merancang sebuah muslihat yang akan mengakhiri perang bukan dengan kekuatan, melainkan dengan tipu daya. Ia mengusulkan pembuatan sebuah kuda kayu raksasa yang berongga, cukup besar untuk menyembunyikan sepasukan prajurit pilihan di dalam perutnya.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''For ten years the Greeks besieged Troy without breaching its mighty walls, said to have been built by the gods Poseidon and Apollo. The war had claimed the lives of great heroes: Hector, defender of Troy, fell at the hands of Achilles, and Achilles himself later died from Paris\'s arrow piercing his heel. The Greek army was weary and despairing, while Troy still stood firm behind its immortal walls. A direct assault had proved futile. So Odysseus, king of Ithaca, famed for his cunning, devised a stratagem that would end the war not by force but by deception. He proposed building a giant hollow wooden horse, large enough to hide a band of chosen warriors within its belly.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Muslihat Sang Kuda',
        headingEn: 'The Stratagem of the Horse',
        body:
            '''Perancang mahir bernama Epeios, dengan bantuan Athena, membangun kuda kayu raksasa itu. Di lambungnya diukir persembahan bagi dewi Athena. Pada malam hari, sepasukan prajurit terbaik Yunani — termasuk Odysseus, Menelaus, dan Neoptolemos putra Akhilleus — merangkak masuk dan bersembunyi di dalam rongga kuda. Sisa pasukan Yunani lalu membakar tenda-tenda mereka, menaiki kapal, dan berlayar seolah menyerah lalu pulang. Namun sesungguhnya mereka hanya bersembunyi di balik pulau Tenedos yang tak jauh dari pantai, menunggu isyarat. Ketika fajar tiba, bangsa Troya terheran-heran mendapati perkemahan musuh telah kosong dan sebuah kuda kayu raksasa berdiri sendirian di dataran. Mereka mengira perang telah usai dan musuh telah pergi selamanya, meninggalkan kuda itu sebagai persembahan perdamaian kepada para dewa.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''A skilled craftsman named Epeius, with the help of Athena, built the giant wooden horse. On its flank was carved a dedication to the goddess Athena. By night, a band of the finest Greek warriors — including Odysseus, Menelaus, and Neoptolemus, son of Achilles — climbed inside and hid within the horse\'s hollow. The rest of the Greek army then burned their tents, boarded their ships, and sailed off as if in surrender and going home. In truth, however, they merely hid behind the island of Tenedos not far from the shore, awaiting the signal. When dawn came, the Trojans were astonished to find the enemy camp empty and a giant wooden horse standing alone on the plain. They believed the war was over and the enemy gone forever, leaving the horse as an offering of peace to the gods.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Peringatan yang Diabaikan',
        headingEn: 'The Warnings Ignored',
        body:
            '''Bangsa Troya berdebat tentang apa yang harus dilakukan terhadap kuda itu. Pendeta Laokoon memperingatkan mereka dengan keras, "Aku takut pada bangsa Yunani, bahkan saat mereka membawa hadiah," lalu melemparkan tombak ke lambung kuda hingga bergema berongga. Namun para dewa yang memihak Yunani campur tangan: dua ular laut raksasa muncul dari lautan dan membelit Laokoon beserta kedua putranya hingga tewas, sehingga rakyat Troya mengira ia dihukum karena menodai persembahan suci. Sementara itu, seorang Yunani bernama Sinon sengaja tertangkap dan berpura-pura membelot. Dengan cerdik ia meyakinkan Troya bahwa kuda itu persembahan untuk Athena, dan jika dibawa masuk ke kota akan membuat Troya tak terkalahkan. Putri Kassandra, yang dikutuk agar ramalannya tak pernah dipercaya, meratap bahwa kuda itu membawa kehancuran — tetapi seperti biasa, tak seorang pun menghiraukannya.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''The Trojans debated what to do with the horse. The priest Laocoon warned them sternly, "I fear the Greeks, even when they bring gifts," and hurled a spear into the horse\'s flank until it echoed hollow. But the gods who favoured the Greeks intervened: two giant sea serpents rose from the ocean and coiled around Laocoon and his two sons, crushing them to death, so the Trojans believed he was punished for defiling a sacred offering. Meanwhile, a Greek named Sinon allowed himself to be captured and pretended to have defected. Cunningly he convinced the Trojans that the horse was an offering to Athena, and that if brought inside the city it would make Troy invincible. The princess Cassandra, cursed so that her prophecies were never believed, wailed that the horse brought destruction — but as ever, no one heeded her.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Kejatuhan Troya',
        headingEn: 'The Fall of Troy',
        body:
            '''Terbujuk oleh tipu daya Sinon dan kematian Laokoon, bangsa Troya merobohkan sebagian tembok mereka dan menyeret kuda kayu itu masuk ke dalam kota sebagai piala kemenangan. Sepanjang hari mereka berpesta pora merayakan berakhirnya perang, mabuk oleh anggur dan kegembiraan, hingga larut malam seluruh kota tertidur lelap tanpa penjagaan. Ketika malam sunyi tiba, Sinon menyalakan api sebagai isyarat, dan para prajurit yang bersembunyi merangkak turun dari perut kuda. Mereka membuka gerbang kota, dan pasukan Yunani yang telah kembali berlayar dari Tenedos menyerbu masuk. Troya yang tak menaruh curiga dibantai dalam kegelapan. Api melalap istana dan rumah-rumah; Raja Priamos dibunuh di altarnya oleh Neoptolemos; para pria ditumpas dan para wanita ditawan. Demikianlah kota agung Troya, yang bertahan sepuluh tahun, runtuh dalam satu malam oleh tipu daya.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''Persuaded by Sinon\'s deceit and Laocoon\'s death, the Trojans tore down part of their wall and dragged the wooden horse into the city as a trophy of victory. All day they feasted to celebrate the war\'s end, drunk with wine and joy, until late at night the whole city fell into a deep, unguarded sleep. When the silent night came, Sinon lit a fire as a signal, and the hidden warriors climbed down from the horse\'s belly. They opened the city gates, and the Greek army, which had sailed back from Tenedos, poured inside. The unsuspecting Troy was slaughtered in the darkness. Fire consumed the palace and houses; King Priam was killed at his altar by Neoptolemus; the men were cut down and the women taken captive. Thus the great city of Troy, which had held out for ten years, fell in a single night through deception.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Sisa-Sisa Reruntuhan',
        headingEn: 'The Aftermath of Ruin',
        body:
            '''Ketika fajar menyingsing, Troya hanyalah reruntuhan yang membara. Menelaus menemukan kembali Helen dan, meski semula hendak membunuhnya, membawanya pulang ke Sparta sebagai istrinya lagi. Para wanita bangsawan Troya menghadapi nasib pahit: Ratu Hekabe dijadikan budak, dan putri Kassandra diseret Agamemnon sebagai tawanan. Cucu Priamos yang masih bayi, Astianaks, dilempar dari tembok kota agar tak ada keturunan Hektor yang tersisa. Namun tidak semua binasa: pahlawan Troya bernama Aeneas berhasil melarikan diri dari kota yang terbakar, memanggul ayahnya yang tua dan menuntun putranya, membawa serta dewa-dewa pelindung Troya. Sesuai takdir yang telah digariskan, Aeneas kelak mengembara ke Italia dan menjadi leluhur bangsa Romawi. Kemenangan Yunani pun ternoda: banyak pahlawan mati dalam pelayaran pulang, dihukum para dewa atas kekejaman mereka di Troya.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''When dawn broke, Troy was but a smouldering ruin. Menelaus found Helen again and, though at first he meant to kill her, took her home to Sparta as his wife once more. The noblewomen of Troy met a bitter fate: Queen Hecuba was made a slave, and the princess Cassandra was dragged off by Agamemnon as a captive. Priam\'s infant grandson, Astyanax, was thrown from the city wall so that no descendant of Hector might remain. Yet not all perished: the Trojan hero Aeneas managed to escape the burning city, carrying his aged father on his back and leading his son, bearing away the protector gods of Troy. As destiny had ordained, Aeneas would one day wander to Italy and become the ancestor of the Roman people. The Greek victory was also stained: many heroes died on the voyage home, punished by the gods for their cruelty at Troy.''',
      ),
    ],
    characters: [
