    ],
    impact:
        '''Kuda Troya mengakhiri perang sepuluh tahun dan menghancurkan kota agung Troya dalam satu malam, membuktikan kemenangan akal atas kekuatan. Kejatuhan Troya menyebarkan para pahlawan ke seluruh dunia: Odysseus mengembara sepuluh tahun untuk pulang, Agamemnon dibunuh sekembalinya, dan Aeneas mengungsi ke Italia untuk menjadi leluhur Roma. Peristiwa ini menjadi puncak siklus epik Troya dan sumber ilham abadi bagi sastra Yunani dan Romawi.''',
    impactEn:
        '''The Trojan Horse ended a ten-year war and destroyed the great city of Troy in a single night, proving the victory of cunning over force. Troy\'s fall scattered the heroes across the world: Odysseus wandered ten years to return home, Agamemnon was murdered upon his arrival, and Aeneas fled to Italy to become the ancestor of Rome. This event was the climax of the Trojan epic cycle and an eternal source of inspiration for Greek and Roman literature.''',
    meaning:
        '''Kuda Troya menjadi lambang universal tipu daya yang menyusup lewat kepercayaan, sehingga istilah "kuda Troya" kini berarti muslihat yang menghancurkan dari dalam. Kisah ini mengajarkan bahaya kesombongan dan kelengahan pada saat kemenangan tampak di depan mata, serta nilai kewaspadaan terhadap hadiah yang terlalu indah. Ia juga mengagungkan kecerdikan Odysseus, menegaskan keyakinan Yunani bahwa akal budi dapat menaklukkan apa yang tak bisa ditembus kekuatan.''',
    meaningEn:
        '''The Trojan Horse became a universal symbol of deception that infiltrates through trust, so that the term "Trojan horse" now means a ruse that destroys from within. The tale teaches the danger of pride and carelessness at the very moment victory seems at hand, and the value of wariness toward gifts that are too fine. It also exalts the cunning of Odysseus, affirming the Greek belief that intellect can conquer what force cannot breach.''',
  ),
  MythStory(
    id: 'greek-odysseus',
    mythology: 'Greek',
    icon: '🌊',
    title: 'Pengembaraan Odysseus',
    titleEn: 'The Odyssey of Odysseus',
    summary:
        'Sepulang dari Troya, Odysseus mengarungi laut selama sepuluh tahun, melawan Cyclops, Circe, Sirene, serta Scylla dan Charybdis, sebelum akhirnya kembali ke Ithaka.',
    summaryEn:
        'Returning from Troy, Odysseus roams the seas for ten years, facing the Cyclops, Circe, the Sirens, and Scylla and Charybdis, before finally reaching Ithaca.',
    timeline: 'Zaman Pahlawan · Kepulangan dari Troya',
    timelineEn: 'Age of Heroes · The Return from Troy',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Latar Belakang',
        headingEn: 'Background',
        body:
            '''Setelah Troya jatuh berkat muslihat kuda kayunya, Odysseus, raja Ithaka yang cerdik, berlayar pulang bersama pasukannya. Namun perjalanan pulang yang seharusnya singkat berubah menjadi pengembaraan sepuluh tahun yang penuh derita, karena ia telah menimbulkan kemurkaan para dewa. Di rumah, di pulau Ithaka, menanti istrinya yang setia, Penelope, dan putra mereka, Telemakhos, yang tumbuh dewasa tanpa mengenal ayahnya. Odysseus rindu pulang, tetapi laut dikuasai Poseidon, dewa lautan yang kelak menaruh dendam kepadanya. Kisah pengembaraannya, yang dituturkan Homerus dalam wiracarita Odyssey, mengisahkan bagaimana kecerdikan dan ketabahan seorang manusia diuji habis-habisan oleh monster, penyihir, godaan, dan amukan para dewa, sampai ia kehilangan seluruh anak buahnya sebelum akhirnya menjejakkan kaki kembali di tanah airnya.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''After Troy fell through the ruse of his wooden horse, Odysseus, the cunning king of Ithaca, set sail for home with his men. But what should have been a short voyage home turned into a ten-year ordeal of suffering, for he had incurred the wrath of the gods. At home, on the island of Ithaca, his faithful wife Penelope waited, and their son Telemachus grew to manhood without knowing his father. Odysseus longed to return, but the sea was ruled by Poseidon, the god of the ocean who would come to bear him a grudge. The tale of his wanderings, told by Homer in the epic Odyssey, recounts how one man\'s cunning and endurance were tested to the utmost by monsters, sorceresses, temptations, and the fury of the gods, until he lost all his companions before at last setting foot again upon his homeland.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Cyclops dan Murka Poseidon',
        headingEn: 'The Cyclops and Poseidon\'s Wrath',
        body:
            '''Salah satu petualangan paling terkenal terjadi di pulau para Cyclops. Odysseus dan anak buahnya memasuki gua raksasa bermata satu bernama Polifemos, putra Poseidon. Sang raksasa mengurung mereka di dalam gua dengan batu besar dan mulai memangsa anak buah Odysseus satu per satu. Dengan kecerdikannya, Odysseus memberi Polifemos anggur kuat hingga mabuk, dan ketika ditanya namanya, ia berkata namanya "Tak Seorang Pun" (Outis). Saat raksasa itu tertidur, Odysseus dan anak buahnya menusuk mata satu-satunya dengan pancang kayu membara hingga buta. Polifemos berteriak minta tolong, tetapi ketika para Cyclops lain bertanya siapa yang menyakitinya, ia menjawab "Tak Seorang Pun", sehingga mereka pergi. Odysseus lolos dengan bergantung di bawah perut domba. Namun karena sombong ia meneriakkan nama aslinya, dan Polifemos memohon kepada ayahnya, Poseidon, agar mengutuk pengembaraan Odysseus.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''One of the most famous adventures took place on the island of the Cyclopes. Odysseus and his men entered the cave of a one-eyed giant named Polyphemus, son of Poseidon. The giant trapped them inside the cave with a great boulder and began to devour Odysseus\'s men one by one. Through his cunning, Odysseus gave Polyphemus strong wine until he was drunk, and when asked his name, he said his name was "Nobody" (Outis). While the giant slept, Odysseus and his men drove a burning wooden stake into his single eye, blinding him. Polyphemus screamed for help, but when the other Cyclopes asked who had hurt him, he answered "Nobody," so they went away. Odysseus escaped by clinging beneath the bellies of the sheep. But out of pride he shouted his real name, and Polyphemus begged his father, Poseidon, to curse Odysseus\'s voyage.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Circe dan Negeri Orang Mati',
        headingEn: 'Circe and the Land of the Dead',
        body:
            '''Setelah kehilangan angin baik dari Aiolos dan diserang para raksasa Laistrigon, Odysseus tiba di pulau Aiaia, tempat sang penyihir Circe. Circe menjamu sebagian anak buah Odysseus lalu mengubah mereka menjadi babi dengan ramuan sihirnya. Dengan bantuan dewa Hermes yang memberinya tumbuhan pelindung bernama moly, Odysseus menahan sihir itu dan memaksa Circe mengembalikan wujud anak buahnya. Ia tinggal setahun di pulau itu sebelum melanjutkan perjalanan. Atas petunjuk Circe, Odysseus lalu berlayar ke tepi dunia menuju Hades, negeri orang mati, untuk menemui arwah peramal buta Teiresias. Di sana ia berbicara dengan arwah-arwah, termasuk ibunya sendiri dan para pahlawan Troya seperti Akhilleus dan Agamemnon. Teiresias menubuatkan jalan pulangnya dan memperingatkan agar anak buahnya tidak mengganggu ternak suci Dewa Matahari Helios di pulau Thrinakia.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''After losing the favourable winds of Aeolus and being attacked by the Laestrygonian giants, Odysseus reached the island of Aeaea, home of the sorceress Circe. Circe feasted some of Odysseus\'s men and then turned them into pigs with her magic potion. With the help of the god Hermes, who gave him a protective plant called moly, Odysseus resisted the spell and forced Circe to restore his men to human form. He stayed a year on the island before continuing his journey. On Circe\'s instructions, Odysseus then sailed to the edge of the world to Hades, the land of the dead, to consult the ghost of the blind prophet Tiresias. There he spoke with the spirits, including his own mother and Trojan War heroes such as Achilles and Agamemnon. Tiresias foretold his way home and warned that his men must not harm the sacred cattle of the Sun God Helios on the island of Thrinacia.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Sirene, Scylla, dan Charybdis',
        headingEn: 'The Sirens, Scylla, and Charybdis',
        body:
            '''Kembali dari negeri orang mati, Odysseus menghadapi bahaya-bahaya yang telah diperingatkan Circe. Pertama, ia melewati para Sirene, makhluk yang nyanyiannya memikat pelaut hingga menabrakkan kapal ke karang. Odysseus menyumbat telinga anak buahnya dengan lilin lebah, tetapi ia sendiri, karena ingin mendengar nyanyian itu, memerintahkan mereka mengikatnya erat ke tiang kapal agar tak dapat melompat. Ia pun selamat sambil mendengar suara mematikan itu. Berikutnya, kapalnya harus melewati selat sempit yang dijaga dua monster: Scylla, makhluk berkepala enam yang menyambar pelaut dari tebing, dan Charybdis, pusaran air raksasa yang menelan seluruh kapal. Odysseus memilih melewati sisi Scylla demi menyelamatkan sebagian besar awak, dan monster itu melahap enam anak buahnya. Dengan hati pilu ia berlayar terus, kehilangan sahabat-sahabatnya demi kelangsungan pelayaran.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''Returning from the land of the dead, Odysseus faced the dangers Circe had warned of. First, he passed the Sirens, creatures whose singing lured sailors to wreck their ships upon the rocks. Odysseus plugged his men\'s ears with beeswax, but he himself, wishing to hear the song, ordered them to bind him tightly to the mast so he could not leap. Thus he survived while hearing that deadly voice. Next, his ship had to pass through a narrow strait guarded by two monsters: Scylla, a six-headed creature that snatched sailors from a cliff, and Charybdis, a giant whirlpool that swallowed whole ships. Odysseus chose to pass on Scylla\'s side to save most of his crew, and the monster devoured six of his men. With an aching heart he sailed on, losing his companions for the sake of the voyage\'s survival.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Ternak Helios dan Calypso',
        headingEn: 'The Cattle of Helios and Calypso',
        body:
            '''Kapal Odysseus mendarat di pulau Thrinakia, tempat ternak suci Dewa Matahari Helios merumput. Meski Odysseus memperingatkan larangan Teiresias, angin buruk menahan mereka berhari-hari hingga kehabisan bekal. Ketika Odysseus tertidur, anak buahnya yang kelaparan menyembelih beberapa sapi suci itu. Helios yang murka menuntut keadilan kepada Zeus, dan begitu mereka berlayar lagi, Zeus menghancurkan kapal dengan halilintar. Seluruh awak tewas; hanya Odysseus yang selamat dengan berpegang pada puing kapal. Ia terdampar di pulau nimfa Calypso, yang mencintainya dan menahannya selama tujuh tahun, bahkan menjanjikan keabadian jika ia mau tinggal. Namun Odysseus tetap merindukan tanah air dan istrinya. Akhirnya, atas perintah Zeus melalui Hermes, Calypso melepasnya. Odysseus membangun rakit dan berlayar, tetapi Poseidon menghancurkannya lagi, hingga ia terdampar di negeri bangsa Faiakia yang ramah.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''Odysseus\'s ship landed on the island of Thrinacia, where the sacred cattle of the Sun God Helios grazed. Though Odysseus warned of Tiresias\'s prohibition, foul winds held them for days until their provisions ran out. When Odysseus fell asleep, his starving men slaughtered some of the sacred cattle. The enraged Helios demanded justice from Zeus, and as soon as they set sail again, Zeus shattered the ship with a thunderbolt. The whole crew perished; only Odysseus survived, clinging to the wreckage. He washed ashore on the island of the nymph Calypso, who loved him and held him for seven years, even promising immortality if he would stay. But Odysseus still longed for his homeland and his wife. At last, by Zeus\'s command through Hermes, Calypso released him. Odysseus built a raft and sailed, but Poseidon wrecked it again, until he washed up in the land of the hospitable Phaeacians.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Kepulangan ke Ithaka',
        headingEn: 'The Return to Ithaca',
        body:
            '''Bangsa Faiakia menyambut Odysseus dengan ramah, mendengarkan seluruh kisah pengembaraannya, lalu mengantarnya pulang dengan kapal mereka. Setelah dua puluh tahun, Odysseus akhirnya menjejakkan kaki di Ithaka. Namun istananya telah dikuasai lebih dari seratus pelamar yang memaksa Penelope menikah lagi sambil menghabiskan hartanya. Dengan bantuan Athena, Odysseus menyamar sebagai pengemis tua untuk menyelidiki keadaan. Ia mengungkap jati dirinya kepada putranya, Telemakhos, dan bersama-sama mereka menyusun rencana. Penelope, yang tetap setia dengan mengulur waktu selama bertahun-tahun, mengumumkan sayembara memanah: siapa yang mampu merentang busur Odysseus dan menembus dua belas kapak akan menjadi suaminya. Hanya Odysseus yang mampu melakukannya. Setelah itu ia dan Telemakhos, dibantu Athena, membantai seluruh pelamar. Odysseus akhirnya bersatu kembali dengan Penelope, dan setelah dua puluh tahun penuh derita, kedamaian pulih di Ithaka.''',
        bodyEn:
            '''The Phaeacians received Odysseus kindly, listened to the whole tale of his wanderings, and then conveyed him home in their ship. After twenty years, Odysseus at last set foot on Ithaca. But his palace had been overrun by more than a hundred suitors who pressed Penelope to remarry while devouring his wealth. With Athena\'s help, Odysseus disguised himself as an old beggar to observe the situation. He revealed his identity to his son, Telemachus, and together they devised a plan. Penelope, who had stayed faithful by stalling for years, announced an archery contest: whoever could string Odysseus\'s bow and shoot through twelve axes would become her husband. Only Odysseus could do it. Then he and Telemachus, aided by Athena, slew all the suitors. Odysseus was at last reunited with Penelope, and after twenty years of suffering, peace was restored to Ithaca.''',
